<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>VT 365 Diesel Engine - 2004 Model Year - OIL COOLER and FILTER HOUSING - Cleaning, Inspection, and Testing -
        Oil Cooler Leaks (Coolant Side)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26509.3.3" svcproctype="test" graphiccount="1">
        <title>Oil Cooler Leaks (Coolant Side)</title>
        <figure id="f2650915" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd13/D1362.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Air pressure leakage test</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Air pressure regulator</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Air adapter (make locally)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Test plate</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The oil filter base must be installed on the oil cooler cover assembly before a pressure test can
                    be done.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Fasten Oil Cooler Test Plate to oil cooler.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install air pressure gauge to EGR cooler coolant outlet port.</para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To prevent personal injury or death, wear safety glasses with side shields to protect eyes. Limit
                    compressed air pressure to 207 kPa (30 psi).
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply 207 kPa (30 psi).</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Spray soapy water around the oil cooler and oil filter base.</para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not submerge the oil cooler in water. Submerging could allow water to
                    be introduced into oil passages, causing engine damage during initial startup.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If leaking, bubbles will be seen between the oil cooler and cover. Replace assembly as
                required.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove soapy water residue and blow off with compressed air.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
